definition.value: A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 3 and 4.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (2R)-3,3,4-trimethyl-6-oxo-3,6-dihydro-1H-pyran-2-yl]acetic acid.
A member of the class of phenylureas that is N-methyl urea substituted by a methoxy group at position 1 and a 3,4-dichlorophenyl group at position 3.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 3 and 4.
A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 3 and 5.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 3 and 5.
A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 3.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 3.
A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 5.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 5.
A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 6.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 6.
A benzoic acid in which any three of the ring hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.
A trimethylbenzoic acid in which the three methyl substituents are located at positions 2, 4 and 6.
A benzoate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any trimethylbenzoic acid.
A trimethylbenzoate in which the three methyl substituents are located at positions 2, 4 and 6.
A trisaccharide that consists of sucrose having an additional fructosyl residue attached to the fructose residue via a beta-(2->6)-linkage.
A menaquinol whose structure comprises a 2-methylbenzohydroquinone nucleus and a side chain of seven isoprenoid units.
A branched tetrasaccharide that consists of sucrose having two additional beta-fructosyl residues attached to the fructose at positions 1 and 6.
A linear tetrasaccharide that consists of sucrose having a beta-D-fructosyl-(2->6)-beta-D-fructosyl moiety attached at position 6 of the fructosyl residue.
An anionic amino-acid residue formed by loss of both protons from the phospho group of an N(pros)-phospho-L-histidine residue, the principal form present at pH 7.3.
A myo-inositol monophosphate in which the phosphate group is located at position 6.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-palmitoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.

The sodium salt of liothyronine. Thought to be more active than levothyroxine and with a rapid (few hours) onset and short duration of action,  liothyronine sodium is used in the treatment of hypothyroidism, particularly in cases of hypothyroid coma.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of any 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol); major species at pH 7.3.
A organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1D-myo-inositol 6-phosphate.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are palmitoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoglycerol in which the glycerol moiety has R-configuration.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by removal of the proton from the phosphate group of glycyl-AMP.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by removal of the proton from the phosphate group of L-threonyl-AMP.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-beta-muramic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is adenosine 5'-monophosphate in which one of the hydroxy groups of the phosphate has been condensed with the carboxylic acid group of glycine.
An N-carbamoylamino acid that is aspartic acid with one of its amino hydrogens replaced by a carbamoyl group.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is adenosine 5'-monophosphate in which one of the hydroxy groups of the phosphate has been condensed with the carboxylic acid group of L-threonine.
The D-enantiomer N-carbamoylaspartic acid.
An organic phosphoramidate anion obtained by removal of the proton from the phosphoramidate OH group of N(epsilon)-(5'-guanylyl)-N(alpha)-acetyl-L-lysine methyl ester; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of N(alpha)-acetyl-L-lysine methyl ester, obtained by protonation of the side-chain amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A cysteine derivative that is the N-carbamoyl derivative of L-cysteine.

A organic phosphoramidate that is guanosine 5'-monophosphate in which one of the hydroxy groups of the phosphate has been condensed with the side chain amino group of N(alpha)-acetyl-L-lysine methyl ester.
The role played by a substance in enhancing the appearance or odour of the human body; a name given to the substance itself or to a component of it.
A triply-charged organic cation obtained by protonation of all three amino groups of aminopropylcadaverine; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino acid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N(alpha)-acetyl-L-lysine with the hydroxy group of methanol.
A polyazaalkane that is the 1,4,11-triaza derivative of undecane.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-acyl-2-octadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-acyl-2-hexadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-acyl-2-tetradecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-acyl-2-dodecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
